"""
MKT Context Commentary — Jonah chapters 1–4 (all 48 verses)
Run: python3 scripts/zc-context-jonah-1-4.py

Jonah is unique in the writing prophets: a narrative about a prophet, not a
prophetic oracle. Historical anchor: Jonah ben Amittai (2 Kgs 14:25) served
during Jeroboam II (793–753 BCE). Nineveh was Assyria's royal capital —
Israel's greatest geopolitical threat. The book's theological question (4:11)
is deliberately left unanswered, forcing the reader to answer it.
"""

import json, pathlib

ROOT = pathlib.Path(__file__).parent.parent

def load_comm(layer, book):
    p = ROOT / 'data' / 'commentary' / layer / f'{book}.json'
    return json.loads(p.read_text()) if p.exists() else {}

def save_comm(layer, book, data):
    p = ROOT / 'data' / 'commentary' / layer / f'{book}.json'
    p.parent.mkdir(parents=True, exist_ok=True)
    p.write_text(json.dumps(data, ensure_ascii=False, indent=None))
    print(f'  wrote {p.relative_to(ROOT)}')

def merge_comm(existing, new_data):
    for ch, verses in new_data.items():
        if ch not in existing:
            existing[ch] = {}
        for v, html in verses.items():
            if v not in existing[ch]:
                existing[ch][v] = html

JONAH = {
  "1": {
    "1": "<p>Jonah ben Amittai is the only writing prophet also named in the historical books: 2 Kings 14:25 records that he prophesied the expansion of Israel's borders under Jeroboam II (793–753 BCE), a period of unprecedented Israelite prosperity and nationalism. The phrase <em>vayehi davar YHWH el-Yonah</em> ('the word of YHWH came to Jonah') is the standard prophetic commissioning formula, placing Jonah squarely within the authentic Israelite prophetic tradition — not outside it. Yet this prophet, uniquely, flees from his commission. The book's narrative problem is introduced at the very first word of divine address.</p>",
    "2": "<p>Nineveh is singled out as the target of YHWH's concern. In the 8th century BCE, Nineveh was one of Assyria's great cities (it would become the empire's sole capital under Sennacherib, 704–681 BCE). The characterization of Nineveh's wickedness (<em>ra'atam</em>) uses the same root as Jonah's extreme displeasure in ch. 4 (<em>vayera le-Yonah ra'ah gedolah</em>). The book plays throughout on <em>ra</em> (evil/disaster): YHWH sees Nineveh's evil; the sailors are afraid of the great evil (storm); YHWH repents of the evil he planned; Jonah is angry over the great evil.</p>",
    "3": "<p><em>Tarshish</em> is traditionally identified with Tartessus in southern Spain (the far western Mediterranean), the opposite direction from Nineveh. Joppa (modern Jaffa) was Israel's main Mediterranean port. Jonah's flight is expressly described as flight <em>millifnei YHWH</em> ('from before the face of YHWH') — but Jonah himself, as a prophet, knows YHWH's omnipresence. Ps 139:7-10 asks 'Where can I go from your Spirit?' The prophet's flight is theologically absurd, and the narrative does not explain it here — the reason emerges only in 4:2. This is deliberate narrative withholding.</p>",
    "4": "<p>The detail that Jonah pays his own fare (<em>vayiten sechara</em>) is realistic narrative: ancient sea voyages required advance payment. But it also underlines the willfulness of his departure — he is not dragged to Tarshish; he actively funds his flight. The ship going 'to Tarshish from before YHWH' mirrors the description of Jonah's own flight, subtly implicating the vessel in the prophet's rebellion.</p>",
    "5": "<p>The storm is YHWH's first act of pursuit. The verb <em>heteyl</em> ('hurled/cast') is used of YHWH casting a great wind upon the sea — the same verb used in v. 4 for the sailors casting cargo overboard and in 1:15 for casting Jonah overboard. The sailors' fear and their prayers to their own gods (plural) establish them as polytheists, yet they are portrayed sympathetically throughout. They are more responsive to the divine than the prophet is. Jonah, meanwhile, has gone below deck and is asleep — an ironic reversal: the pagan sailors cry to their gods while the prophet of YHWH sleeps.</p>",
    "6": "<p>The captain's rebuke of the sleeping prophet — 'What do you mean, O sleeper? Arise, call out to your god!' — uses language structurally parallel to divine commissioning speech. The pagan captain unknowingly exhorts the prophet of YHWH to do exactly what YHWH commanded him to do in v. 2. The irony is bitter: a Gentile ship captain is more attentive to the crisis than the prophet who precipitated it.</p>",
    "7": "<p>Casting lots (<em>goralot</em>) was a common ancient Near Eastern method of determining divine will (cf. Josh 7:14-18; 1 Sam 14:42; Prov 16:33). The lot falls on Jonah without suspense or surprise — the narrative presumes the reader already knows what the sailors do not yet know. The lot's accuracy is not presented as magic but as YHWH's providence guiding the process to its intended outcome.</p>",
    "8": "<p>The sailors' interrogation of Jonah uses four rapid questions, reflecting genuine panic and the need to understand the source of the divine anger pursuing them. 'What is your occupation? Where do you come from? What is your country? Of what people are you?' — these are standard identity questions in the ancient world, which would determine which deity was offended and what ritual response was appropriate.</p>",
    "9": "<p>Jonah's self-identification is theologically loaded: <em>'Ivri anochi ve'et YHWH Elohei hashamayim ani yarei</em> — 'I am a Hebrew, and I fear YHWH, the God of heaven, who made the sea and the dry land.' He identifies himself as a worshiper of the creator God — including the very sea that is threatening them. There is deep irony: the one who most fears YHWH (theoretically) is the one who fled from him. The sailors are terrified not just of the storm but of the new theological information: this man's God controls the sea itself.</p>",
    "10": "<p>The sailors knew Jonah was fleeing from YHWH because he had told them (<em>ki higid lahem</em>). The revelation of v. 9 makes the storm comprehensible: a man fleeing from the God who made the sea, on the sea. The sailors' question — 'What is this you have done?' — is a rebuke, but it is also the question that Jonah cannot answer in this chapter. His silence is eloquent.</p>",
    "11": "<p>The sailors' question to Jonah — 'What shall we do with you, that the sea may quiet down for us?' — is practically motivated but theologically significant: they are asking the prophet of YHWH how to appease YHWH. The storm is intensifying (<em>ki hayam holekh veso'er</em>, 'for the sea was growing more and more tempestuous') — the participle construction indicates continuous action, heightening urgency.</p>",
    "12": "<p>Jonah's instruction — 'Pick me up and hurl me into the sea, and the sea will quiet down for you, for I know it is because of me that this great tempest has come upon you' — contains the only genuine speech in ch. 1 that shows self-awareness. He acknowledges guilt and offers himself as the solution. The theological resonance with substitutionary sacrifice is significant: one man is given up so that the many may be saved. The sailors throw Jonah overboard (1:15) and the sea calms; they are saved. This is the type that Jesus himself names in Matt 12:40.</p>",
    "13": "<p>The sailors try to row to shore before complying with Jonah's instruction — three times the narrative tells us the sea grew worse as they rowed harder. The sailors' reluctance to throw a man overboard shows moral scruple that goes beyond self-interest. They are not villains; they are decent men caught in a catastrophe they did not create. Their attempt to find an alternative to killing Jonah makes their eventual act of casting him overboard more weighty.</p>",
    "14": "<p>The sailors' prayer before throwing Jonah overboard is remarkable: they address YHWH by name — not their own gods, but YHWH, the God Jonah had named. They pray for forgiveness for the bloodshed they are about to commit and acknowledge YHWH's sovereign will ('you, O YHWH, have done as it pleased you'). These Gentile sailors, through their encounter with a rebellious prophet, have come to genuine prayer to the God of Israel. Their conversion is understated but unmistakable.</p>",
    "15": "<p>The moment Jonah is thrown overboard, the sea ceases its raging. The immediacy (no delay) confirms YHWH's involvement: the storm was purposeful, and its cessation is equally purposeful. The sailors' deliverance confirms Jonah's own diagnosis (v. 12) and demonstrates that YHWH's judgment was precisely targeted. The sea narrative ends here; what happens to Jonah is reported separately in v. 17.</p>",
    "16": "<p>The sailors' response to the calm is not relief but worship: they 'feared YHWH exceedingly' (<em>vayiru ha'anashim yir'ah gedolah et YHWH</em>), offered a sacrifice, and made vows. This is covenant language — vows (<em>nedarim</em>) sealed the worshiper to the deity. The Gentile sailors end the chapter as worshipers of YHWH, fulfilling more of the prophetic mission than Jonah himself has at this point. The irony is maximized: the prophet who fled from his Gentile mission inadvertently accomplished part of it on the ship.</p>",
    "17": "<p>YHWH <em>manna</em> (appointed/commissioned) the great fish — the same verb used in 4:6, 7, 8 for the plant, the worm, and the east wind. Everything YHWH deploys in the book is commissioned (manned) for a specific purpose: fish, plant, worm, wind are all YHWH's instruments. The fish is not punishment but rescue — without it, Jonah drowns. The 'three days and three nights' formula appears also in Gen 42:17-18 (Joseph's brothers in custody) and is the formula Jesus appropriates in Matt 12:40 for his time in the tomb. The fish's belly is simultaneously confinement and salvation — the liminal space between death and re-commission.</p>"
  },
  "2": {
    "1": "<p>Jonah's prayer from inside the fish is the only sustained speech of the book before ch. 4. It is composed almost entirely of phrases from the Psalter — scholars have identified allusions to Psalms 3, 5, 18, 22, 30, 31, 42, 46, 69, 86, 88, 116, 120, 130, and 142. This dense intertextuality with lament psalms suggests that the prayer was composed as a deliberate anthology of psalm language, placed on Jonah's lips to make his individual crisis resonate with the whole tradition of Israelite lament and praise.</p>",
    "2": "<p><em>Min beten sheol shivati</em> — 'from the belly of Sheol I cried.' Sheol is the Hebrew underworld, the realm of the dead. Jonah describes the fish's belly as equivalent to Sheol — he was, from his perspective, as good as dead. The parallel 'belly of the fish' / 'belly of Sheol' is deliberate: the fish is simultaneously rescue and entombment, salvation and death-house. This ambivalence is central to the sign Jesus appropriates: the tomb is both death and preparation for resurrection.</p>",
    "3": "<p>The imagery of waves and breakers passing over him (<em>kol mishbarecha vegalecha alay avaru</em>) closely echoes Ps 42:7 ('all your breakers and your waves have gone over me'). The address to YHWH ('you cast me into the deep') frames the drowning not as accident or the sailors' act but as YHWH's doing — Jonah perceives divine agency even in the consequence of his own rebellion. This is theologically mature: he does not blame the sailors.</p>",
    "4": "<p>'I am driven away from your sight' (<em>nigrazti mineged einecha</em>) — the very condition Jonah sought by fleeing. The bitterest irony: his flight from YHWH's presence has now resulted in an experience of being cut off from it that he did not actually want. The exile from God's presence that Jonah chose becomes something he laments. 'Yet I shall again look upon your holy temple' — this anticipatory confidence in restoration, placed amid the depths, is the theological hinge of the psalm.</p>",
    "5": "<p>The 'waters encompassed me to the point of death' (<em>afu mayim ad nefesh</em>) — literally 'waters were up to my soul/life.' The deep (<em>tehom</em>) surrounds him — the same primordial deep (tehom) over which the Spirit hovered in Gen 1:2, now threatening to swallow one of God's own prophets. Seaweed wrapped around his head — the realism of drowning in the sea before the fish swallows him is vividly described.</p>",
    "6": "<p>The descent to 'the roots of the mountains' and 'the bars of the earth forever' (<em>beriche eretz le'olam</em>) — the bars/bolts of Sheol are a common ancient Near Eastern image for the gates of the underworld (cf. Job 38:17; Ps 107:16). Jonah has reached the lowest structural point of the cosmos. The pivot: <em>vata'al mishachat chayai YHWH Elohai</em> — 'yet you brought up my life from the pit, O YHWH my God.' The reversal — descent followed by ascent — is the structural template for the resurrection.</p>",
    "7": "<p>'When my life was fainting away, I remembered YHWH, and my prayer came to you, into your holy temple.' The phrase <em>behit'ateif alay nafshi</em> ('when my life was ebbing away') appears also in Ps 142:3 and Lam 2:12. The act of remembering (<em>zachar</em>) YHWH triggers prayer which reaches the temple — the earthly location of YHWH's presence that Jonah had tried to flee by going to sea. The temple serves as the conduit for prayer from any location, including the depths of the sea.</p>",
    "8": "<p>'Those who pay regard to vain idols forsake their steadfast love (<em>chesed</em>).' The contrast with the Gentile sailors' newly offered vows (1:16) is sharp: those who worship idols are described as forsaking <em>chesed</em> — the covenant love of YHWH — while the very sailors Jonah might have dismissed as pagans have just offered vows to YHWH. Jonah's theology here is conventional orthodox Israelite polemic; the narrative context subverts it by showing Gentiles worshiping YHWH while the prophet languishes in a fish.</p>",
    "9": "<p>'But I with the voice of thanksgiving will sacrifice to you; what I have vowed I will pay. Salvation belongs to YHWH!' (<em>lYHWH hayeshuah</em>.) This climactic declaration — 'the salvation is YHWH's' — is structurally placed at the psalm's conclusion as its theological thesis. It also announces the theme of the whole book: who controls salvation? Who may receive it? The Gentile Ninevites, the sailors, and eventually Jonah himself are all objects of YHWH's salvific mercy. The answer to 'whose salvation?' is YHWH alone.</p>",
    "10": "<p>YHWH commands the fish and it vomits Jonah onto dry land. The verb <em>vayaqo</em> ('vomited') is undignified — perhaps intentionally so. Jonah has been marinating in the fish's belly for three days; the book is not trying to beautify his ordeal. The 'dry land' (<em>hayabashah</em>) echoes the creation language of Gen 1:9-10 and the sea narrative in ch. 1 ('who made the sea and the dry land,' 1:9) — Jonah is restored to the ordered world of creation after his journey through the watery chaos.</p>"
  },
  "3": {
    "1": "<p>'Then the word of YHWH came to Jonah the second time' (<em>vayehi debar YHWH el-Yonah shenit</em>). The identical commissioning formula as 1:1 — but with the crucial addition: <em>shenit</em>, 'a second time.' YHWH reissues the commission without rebuke or explanation. No punishment for the flight, no demand for repentance. The second call simply comes, as if continuing a sentence interrupted by three days of fish-belly delay. This pattern — YHWH recommissioning a failed prophet — is part of the book's grace argument.</p>",
    "2": "<p>The commission is slightly modified: now Jonah is told to proclaim 'the message that I tell you' (<em>et-hadvar asher anochi dover elecha</em>) rather than 'cry out against it' (1:2). The ambiguity of the actual message is maintained — Jonah still doesn't know exactly what he will say until he gets there. This is consistent with the prophetic experience of receiving the specific word only at the moment of delivery (cf. Jer 1:7-9).</p>",
    "3": "<p>'So Jonah arose and went to Nineveh, according to the word of YHWH.' The obedience is unadorned — no comment on Jonah's inner state, no indication of reluctance or enthusiasm. The description of Nineveh as 'an exceedingly great city, a three-day journey' (<em>ir gedolah le'lohim mahalakh shloshet yamim</em>) — literally 'great to God,' a Hebrew superlative — establishes Nineveh's enormity. Archaeological evidence confirms that greater Nineveh (including suburbs) could require several days to traverse. The 'three-day journey' may also echo the three days in the fish.</p>",
    "4": "<p>Jonah's message is the shortest prophetic oracle in the Hebrew Bible: <em>od arba'im yom veNinveh nehpachet</em> — 'Yet forty days, and Nineveh will be overthrown.' Five Hebrew words. The number forty has biblical resonance (forty days of rain in the flood; forty years in the wilderness; forty days of Moses on Sinai; forty days of Elijah's journey). The verb <em>nehpachet</em> (from <em>hafach</em>) means 'overturned/overthrown' — used of Sodom and Gomorrah (Gen 19:25, 29; Amos 4:11; Deut 29:23). The oracle says nothing about repentance as a condition. It is pure announcement of doom — and yet the Ninevites repent anyway.</p>",
    "5": "<p>The Ninevites 'believed God' (<em>vayaaminu anshei Ninveh be'lohim</em>) — the same language used of Abraham's faith in Gen 15:6 (<em>vehemin baYHWH</em>). The word used here is <em>Elohim</em> rather than YHWH — consistent with Gentile usage throughout the book. The proclamation of a fast and putting on sackcloth was standard ancient Near Eastern mourning and penitential practice; an Assyrian king ordering national penitential rites is historically plausible (Assyrian records document such practices). The response is universal: 'from the greatest to the least.'</p>",
    "6": "<p>The king of Nineveh hears Jonah's message, rises from his throne, removes his royal robe, covers himself with sackcloth, and sits in ashes — a complete ritual reversal of royal dignity. The detail of his sitting in ashes (<em>vayeshev al-ha'efer</em>) echoes the mourning of Job (Job 2:8) and the expected posture of genuine penitence. The king's descent from throne to ash heap is the narrative illustration of the theological principle: divine judgment levels human pride.</p>",
    "7": "<p>The royal decree that follows is remarkable in ancient Near Eastern context: it commands not only humans but also animals to fast and wear sackcloth (<em>ha'adam vehab'hemah, habakar vehatson al-yit'amu meumah</em>). Animal participation in mourning rites is attested in Persian-period texts (Herodotus records Persians cutting their horses' manes in mourning), and including animals in communal fasting heightens the totality of the communal act. The decree also commands a turning (<em>yashUVU</em>) from evil ways.</p>",
    "8": "<p>The decree demands both ritual act (fasting, sackcloth, animals included) and moral change: 'let everyone turn from his evil way and from the violence (<em>chamas</em>) that is in his hands.' <em>Chamas</em> (violence, wrongdoing) is the precise charge leveled against the pre-flood generation in Gen 6:11: 'the earth was filled with <em>chamas</em>.' The Ninevite king's diagnosis — the violence that is in our hands — is self-aware in a way that many Israelite kings never manage in the text of the Hebrew Bible.</p>",
    "9": "<p>'Who knows? God may turn and relent and turn from his fierce anger, so that we may not perish.' The phrase <em>mi yodea</em> ('who knows?') expresses genuine uncertainty about divine response — not as skepticism but as humble openness. The same phrase appears in Joel 2:14 ('who knows whether he will not turn and relent') and 2 Sam 12:22 (David's fast for his dying son). The Ninevites are not certain repentance will work; they repent without a guarantee. This is theologically significant: their repentance is genuine rather than transactional.</p>",
    "10": "<p>'When God saw what they did, how they turned from their evil way, God relented of the disaster that he had said he would do to them, and he did not do it.' The verb <em>vayinachem</em> ('relented/repented') is the same used in Exod 32:14 when YHWH relents from the golden calf disaster after Moses' intercession. It indicates genuine divine responsiveness to human action — not divine caprice or unreliability, but the consistent character of a God who responds to repentance. This is the climax of the chapter, and it sets up the devastating contrast of ch. 4: the same character of YHWH that saves Nineveh is the character that Jonah knew all along — and fled to prevent.</p>"
  },
  "4": {
    "1": "<p>'But it displeased Jonah exceedingly, and he was angry' (<em>vayera el-Yonah ra'ah gedolah vayichar lo</em>). Now the narrative delivers the delayed explanation for ch. 1's flight. The prophet's anger is directed not at divine injustice but at divine mercy. The language is extreme: <em>ra'ah gedolah</em> — a great evil/disaster — the same phrase used of the great storm in 1:12 and Nineveh's wickedness in 1:2. For Jonah, YHWH's mercy on Nineveh is as catastrophic as a storm at sea or a city's wickedness. The narrative's irony has been building since ch. 1; here it breaks open.</p>",
    "2": "<p>Jonah's prayer reveals his theology and his motivation: 'Is this not what I said when I was yet in my country? That is why I made haste to flee to Tarshish; for I knew that you are a gracious God and merciful, slow to anger and abounding in steadfast love, and relenting from disaster.' The theological formula Jonah quotes — <em>El chanun verachum, erech apayim verav chesed venicham al hara'ah</em> — is almost verbatim from Exod 34:6-7, the great YHWH self-disclosure after the golden calf. This is orthodox Israelite theology. Jonah's problem is not ignorance of YHWH's character; he knew it perfectly — and fled precisely because he feared it would apply to Nineveh.</p>",
    "3": "<p>'Therefore now, O YHWH, please take my life from me, for it is better for me to die than to live.' Jonah's death wish echoes Elijah's in 1 Kgs 19:4 ('it is enough; now, O YHWH, take away my life, for I am no better than my fathers'). Both prophets express suicidal ideation after prophetic crisis. Jonah's crisis is not exhaustion or persecution but rather his theological discomfort with YHWH's mercy extending to enemies. He would prefer death to living in a world where Nineveh is spared.</p>",
    "4": "<p>YHWH's response is a single question: 'Do you do well to be angry?' (<em>hahetev chara lach</em>). The question is open rather than condemnatory. YHWH does not rebuke; he interrogates. This is the rhetorical strategy of the book's final chapter: instead of declaring Jonah wrong, YHWH draws out the logic of Jonah's position through experience (the plant), then mirrors it back with a final unanswered question (4:11). The divine pedagogy here is experiential and dialogical.</p>",
    "5": "<p>Jonah goes outside the city to sit and watch what will happen to it. He still harbors hope that YHWH will destroy Nineveh — or perhaps he cannot accept the repentance's permanence. He makes himself a booth (<em>sukkah</em>) for shade, a temporary shelter that recalls the Feast of Booths (Sukkot) — pilgrimage, dependence, and impermanence. Jonah sits outside a foreign city under his makeshift shelter, watching for a destruction that will not come.</p>",
    "6": "<p>YHWH appoints (<em>manna</em>) a plant — the <em>qiqayon</em>, usually identified as the castor-oil plant (Ricinus communis), which can grow very rapidly. The plant grows overnight to provide shade over Jonah's head and relieves his discomfort. Jonah 'was exceedingly glad' (<em>vayismach Yonah al-haqiqayon simchah gedolah</em>) — the first time in the book that Jonah experiences joy, and it is over a plant. His emotional investment in the plant prepares the lesson of vv. 10-11.</p>",
    "7": "<p>At dawn the next day, YHWH appoints (<em>manna</em>) a worm (<em>tola'at</em>) that attacks the plant so that it withers. The worm is YHWH's instrument just as the fish was — all of creation is at YHWH's disposal. The reversal is swift: the joy of v. 6 becomes loss in v. 7. Jonah's shade is removed, setting up the conditions for the final object lesson.</p>",
    "8": "<p>YHWH appoints (<em>manna</em>) a 'scorching east wind' (<em>ruach qadim charishit</em>) — the sirocco, the desert wind that blows from the east in the Near East and raises temperatures dramatically while lowering humidity. Jonah is exposed, hot, and despairing. Again he wishes to die: 'It is better for me to die than to live.' The parallel with v. 3 is exact: the same death wish, now triggered by the plant's loss rather than Nineveh's salvation. YHWH asks again: 'Do you do well to be angry for the plant?' Jonah doubles down: 'Yes, I do well to be angry, angry enough to die.'</p>",
    "9": "<p>Jonah's response — 'Yes, I do well to be angry, angry enough to die' — is the most theologically revealing line he speaks. He has admitted that his anger over the plant is worth dying over. He is more exercised over the loss of a gourd than over the fate of 120,000 people. This is not cruelty but proportionality: Jonah's value system assigns more weight to his personal comfort and his national interests than to Gentile lives. YHWH's final speech uses this admission against him.</p>",
    "10": "<p>YHWH's final speech begins: 'You pity (<em>chasta</em>) the plant for which you did not labor, nor did you make it grow, which came into being in a night and perished in a night.' The key verb <em>chus</em> (to pity/spare) is used only here and in v. 11. Jonah has an emotional attachment to the plant; he did nothing to create it; it lasted one night. Yet he grieves its loss. The argument from lesser to greater (<em>qal vachomer</em>) is established: if Jonah can pity a plant he didn't create, how much more should YHWH pity a city?</p>",
    "11": "<p>'And should I not pity (<em>lo achus</em>) Nineveh, that great city, in which there are more than 120,000 persons who do not know their right hand from their left, and also much cattle?' The final question of the book — and it is left deliberately unanswered. '120,000 who do not know their right hand from their left' is typically interpreted as infants or young children (not yet morally responsible), making the population figure much larger. 'And also much cattle' adds a note of absurdist pathos: YHWH's care for livestock mirrors his care for the ignorant. The book ends mid-conversation, Jonah's response unrecorded — the reader must answer YHWH's question for themselves.</p>"
  }
}

def main():
    c = load_comm('mkt-context', 'jonah')
    merge_comm(c, JONAH)
    save_comm('mkt-context', 'jonah', c)
    print('jonah mkt-context: merged chapters 1-4')

if __name__ == '__main__':
    main()
